Your mini-roadmap should fit on one page. It should allow a manager, business owner, or project team to understand the idea without a long meeting.

Use this structure.

### 1. Business problem

Which pain point do you want to reduce?

Examples:

- too much time spent writing meeting minutes;
- customer complaints are poorly classified;
- internal procedures are hard to find;
- manual reporting is too slow;
- HR documents are inconsistent;
- commercial answers vary too much.

### 2. AI use case

What will AI do concretely?

Example:

> AI will help the support team classify customer complaints by theme, urgency, and recommended action type.

### 3. Users

Who will use the system?

- employees;
- managers;
- support team;
- HR;
- finance;
- sales;
- students;
- customers;
- partners.

### 4. Required data

What data will be used?

Also indicate its sensitivity level:

- public;
- internal;
- confidential;
- personal;
- sensitive.

### 5. Expected benefits

Choose two or three benefits maximum:

- reduce delay;
- improve quality;
- reduce errors;
- standardize answers;
- make information easier to access;
- improve activity monitoring.

### 6. Risks and guardrails

State the main risks and protection rules.

Examples:

- anonymization;
- approved tool;
- human review;
- limited access;
- logging;
- no automatic decision;
- legal or compliance review when needed.

### 7. First action in 30 days

A credible roadmap ends with a short action.

Examples:

- map 20 recurring requests;
- collect 10 non-sensitive documents;
- test 5 prompts with a pilot team;
- define an evaluation grid;
- measure time saved on one task.

