### Pedagogical intent

Ella should verify that the learner can move from a general AI idea to a structured, realistic, and responsible use case.

The checkpoint should directly prepare the final lab.

### Suggested situation for dynamic checkpoint generation

Ask the learner to choose a problem in their department or in a department proposed by Ella: HR, finance, marketing, customer support, operations, administration, education, IT.

Ella asks the learner to formulate:

- the business problem;
- the AI use case;
- the users;
- the required data;
- two measurable benefits;
- two risks;
- two guardrails;
- one first action in the next 30 days.

### What a good answer should contain

A good answer must be concrete. It must describe a limited, testable, and useful use.

It should also mention data, risks, and human control when the use touches internal or personal information.

### Common mistakes to detect

- Proposing a tool without a clear problem.
- Writing an objective that is too broad, such as "digitalize the whole department."
- Forgetting the required data.
- Forgetting risks.
- Promising full automation when controlled assistance is enough.
- Proposing a benefit that cannot be measured.

### Possible Socratic follow-ups

- "Which precise pain point do you want to reduce?"
- "Who will use this solution every day?"
- "What data must you provide to the AI?"
- "How will you know the project succeeded?"
- "Which part must remain under human control?"
- "Which action can you launch in the next 30 days?"

### Validation criteria

Ella can validate if the learner:

- formulates a precise business problem;
- proposes a limited and useful AI use case;
- identifies users and data;
- proposes at least two measurable benefits;
- identifies risks and guardrails;
- defines a realistic first action.
